{
  "texts": [
    "Furthermore, the forming voltage of 2D material-based memristors typically exceeds 1 V, which may surpass the voltage supply tolerance of advanced CMOS transistors, thereby limiting the functionality of access transistors.",
    "Secondly, device switching speed can be impeded by the latency in selectors 1 3 and transistors.",
    "For instance, in the case of state-of-the-art CMOS/h-BN heterogeneous integration 1T1R CBAs, a high latency of 230 μs during programming is demonstrated, which is considerably slower than memristor-only devices (10 ns) [89].",
    "Moreover, the disparity between the reset current of 2D memristors (1 mA) and the ON-state current of selectors/transistors (100 μA) necessitates a larger area for the selector and transistor arrays to provide sufficient current for switching 2D material-based memristors [34,36,55,71,73,136].",
    "In summary, further investigation is warranted for selectors and transistors with a high ON-current, high ON/ OFF ratio, and low latency."
  ]
}